{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "In the works by Lockwood et al (2007) and Hall et al (2009), a trend of positive correlation between log[mean(R ′ HK)] and log[STD(R ′ HK)] is shown for the solar-like stars.",
    "Like the Ca II H and K lines, the hydrogen Hα line is another commonly used spectral line to indicate chromospheric activity of solar-like stars (e.g., Cram and Mullan 1979; Herbig 1985; Pasquini and Pallavicini 1991; Lyra and Porto de Mello 2005; Meunier and Delfosse 2009).",
    "For F-type and G-type stars, the Hα line mainly exhibits an absorption-line profile, and the enhanced line-core radiation due to stellar activity manifests as the filling-in of the absorption line.",
    "For K-type and later type stars, if the activity intensity is high enough, the line-core radiation may exceed the continuum and the Hα line can exhibit an emission-line profile (e.g., Robinson et al 1990).",
    "Gomes da Silva et al (2014, 2022) and Meunier et al (2022) analyzed the variability of Hα activity of FGK main-sequence stars using the long-term (several years) observation data of the HARPS spectrograph and investigated the correlation between the stellar Hα activity and Ca II H and K activity."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
